---
import ContentApp from '../../layouts/ContentApp.astro'

const sections = [
  { id: 'threat-model', label: 'Threat model' },
  { id: 'what-pai-protects', label: 'What PAI protects' },
  { id: 'what-pai-does-not-protect', label: "What it doesn't protect" },
  { id: 'known-limitations', label: 'Known limitations' },
  { id: 'vulnerability-disclosure', label: 'Vulnerability disclosure' },
]
---

<ContentApp
  title="Security"
  description="PAI threat model, security guarantees, and vulnerability disclosure policy."
>
  <nav slot="sidebar">
    <p class="sb-brand">Security</p>
    {sections.map((s) => <a href={`#${s.id}`} class="sb-link">{s.label}</a>)}
    <hr class="sb-divider" />
    <a
      href="https://github.com/nirholas/pai/security/advisories/new"
      class="sb-link"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer"
      style="font-size:0.8125rem;color:var(--pai-red)"
    >
      Report a vulnerability ↗
    </a>
  </nav>

  <h1>Security</h1>
  <p>
    PAI's security model is based on defense-in-depth and operational security. This page documents
    what PAI protects, what it doesn't, and how to report vulnerabilities.
  </p>

  <!-- Threat model -->
  <section id="threat-model">
    <h2>Threat model</h2>
    <p>
      PAI is designed for users who need a private, portable AI workstation — journalists,
      researchers, security professionals, and privacy-conscious individuals. The primary threats
      are:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Cloud AI providers collecting and analyzing your prompts</li>
      <li>Network observers logging your AI usage and traffic patterns</li>
      <li>Forensic analysis of the machine you used PAI on</li>
      <li>Tracking across sessions via persistent identifiers</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- What PAI protects -->
  <section id="what-pai-protects">
    <h2>What PAI protects against</h2>
    <div class="threat-grid">
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--green">Protected</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Cloud AI data harvesting</strong>
          <p>All inference is local via Ollama. Your prompts never leave your hardware.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--green">Protected</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Forensic analysis of host machine</strong>
          <p>
            PAI is amnesic — no disk writes, no mount of the host drive. RAM is cleared on
            shutdown.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--green">Protected</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Network-based tracking across sessions</strong>
          <p>
            MAC address randomized on every boot. New identity, new device fingerprint each time.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--green">Protected</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Local network attacks on AI services</strong>
          <p>
            UFW blocks all inbound connections. Ollama and PAI UI are localhost-only; unreachable
            from the network.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--yellow">Opt-in</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Network surveillance and traffic analysis</strong>
          <p>
            With <code>sudo pai-privacy on</code>, all traffic is routed through Tor. DNS resolves
            via Tor. Without Tor, outbound traffic is protected by the firewall but not anonymized.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--yellow">Opt-in</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Persistent data exposure</strong>
          <p>
            Without persistence: nothing survives shutdown. With persistence: data is LUKS2-encrypted
            on the USB drive.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What PAI does NOT protect -->
  <section id="what-pai-does-not-protect">
    <h2>What PAI does not protect against</h2>
    <div class="threat-grid">
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--red">Not mitigated</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Physical hardware attacks</strong>
          <p>
            Keyloggers, hardware implants, or surveillance cameras on the host machine are out of
            scope. PAI cannot protect against an adversary with physical access to the hardware.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--red">Not mitigated</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Compromised BIOS/UEFI firmware</strong>
          <p>
            A tampered firmware can subvert the boot process before PAI loads. Verify the machine is
            trustworthy before use.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--red">Not mitigated</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Cold boot attacks</strong>
          <p>
            RAM retains data briefly after power-off on some hardware. Mitigated by full shutdown
            (not sleep/hibernate) and allowing the machine to rest before physical access.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--red">Not mitigated</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Compromised USB drive</strong>
          <p>
            Always verify the ISO checksum before flashing. A tampered ISO can contain malicious
            code that PAI cannot detect.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="threat-entry">
        <div class="risk-badge risk-badge--yellow">Partial</div>
        <div class="threat-content">
          <strong>Global adversary (ISP + exit node correlation)</strong>
          <p>
            Tor protects against most network observers, but a global passive adversary who controls
            both the entry and exit point of a Tor circuit can perform correlation attacks. This is a
            known Tor limitation, not PAI-specific.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Known limitations -->
  <section id="known-limitations">
    <h2>Known limitations</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>CPU-only inference</strong> — GPU drivers are stripped to keep the ISO small. This
        reduces the attack surface but also limits speed to 5–20 tokens/sec on most hardware.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No Secure Boot support</strong> — PAI's bootloader is not signed. Secure Boot must
        be disabled. Signed bootloader support is on the roadmap.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tor is opt-in</strong> — by default, outbound traffic is not anonymized. Enable Tor
        with <code>sudo pai-privacy on</code> for network anonymity.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Model downloads are not anonymous</strong> — unless Tor is enabled before pulling a
        model, the download reveals your IP to the model host.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>ISO signing</strong> — GPG-signed releases are planned; unsigned builds should be
        verified by SHA-256 checksum until then.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- Vulnerability disclosure -->
  <section id="vulnerability-disclosure">
    <h2>Vulnerability disclosure</h2>
    <p>
      PAI follows responsible disclosure. If you discover a security vulnerability, please report it
      privately before public disclosure.
    </p>

    <h3>How to report</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Use GitHub's private vulnerability reporting:
        <a
          href="https://github.com/nirholas/pai/security/advisories/new"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >
          Report a vulnerability ↗
        </a>
      </li>
      <li>
        Or email <code>security@pai.direct</code> with "PAI Security" in the subject.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h3>What to include</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Description of the vulnerability and affected component</li>
      <li>Steps to reproduce</li>
      <li>Potential impact and severity assessment</li>
      <li>Any suggested fixes (optional but appreciated)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Response timeline</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Acknowledgment</strong>: within 48 hours</li>
      <li><strong>Assessment</strong>: within 7 days</li>
      <li><strong>Fix</strong>: coordinated with reporter, typically within 30–90 days</li>
      <li><strong>Disclosure</strong>: after fix is released and users have time to update</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      We do not offer a bug bounty program at this time, but we credit researchers in release notes.
    </p>
  </section>
</ContentApp>

<style>
  .notice {
    background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.08);
    border: 1px solid rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.3);
    border-radius: var(--r-window);
    padding: var(--s-3) var(--s-4);
    margin-bottom: var(--s-6);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    max-width: 72ch;
  }

  .notice code {
    background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.15);
    border-color: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.2);
    color: var(--pai-yellow);
  }

  .threat-grid {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--s-3);
    max-width: 72ch;
    margin-bottom: var(--s-5);
  }

  .threat-entry {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--s-3);
    align-items: flex-start;
    padding: var(--s-3) var(--s-4);
    border-radius: var(--r-window);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    background: var(--bg-elev);
  }

  .risk-badge {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    padding: 3px 8px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    font-size: 0.6875rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    white-space: nowrap;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }

  .risk-badge--green {
    background: rgba(74, 222, 128, 0.15);
    color: var(--pai-green);
    border: 1px solid rgba(74, 222, 128, 0.3);
  }

  .risk-badge--yellow {
    background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.15);
    color: var(--pai-yellow);
    border: 1px solid rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.3);
  }

  .risk-badge--red {
    background: rgba(248, 113, 113, 0.15);
    color: var(--pai-red);
    border: 1px solid rgba(248, 113, 113, 0.3);
  }

  .threat-content {
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 0;
  }

  .threat-content strong {
    display: block;
    color: var(--fg);
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }

  .threat-content p {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    line-height: 1.5;
    max-width: none;
  }
</style>
